Core Invariants

Invariant 1 — Signal Before Scale

Nothing should propagate before its load-bearing signal is known.

Invariant 2 — Pressure Before Trust

Anything that cannot survive bounded stress should not be promoted.

Invariant 3 — Repair Before Pride

Weakness exposed is not failure; unrepaired weakness is.

Invariant 4 — Conversion Before Discard

Apparent flaws should be examined for leverage before removal.

Invariant 5 — Time Is a Filter

Anything that cannot survive repetition, timing, and cadence is not yet stable.

Invariant 6 — Translation Preserves, Not Redeems

Rendering can package signal, but cannot create it from nothing.

Invariant 7 — Others Are the Real Test

A construct proves itself when others can use it without destroying its essence.

⸻

Success Criteria

A Signalforge output is considered successful when it:
	•	remains coherent under pressure
	•	is understandable in plain language
	•	can be rendered across mediums
	•	is usable by other operators
	•	produces measurable real-world effect
	•	improves through feedback
	•	preserves core invariants during adaptation

⸻

Failure Modes

1. Aesthetic Shell

Looks polished but has no load-bearing structure.

2. Narrative Inflation

Sounds profound but does not survive verification.

3. Unrepaired Fracture

Pressure revealed a flaw, but it was merely renamed.

4. Translation Delusion

Assumption that formatting or tooling can fix weak signal.

5. Operator Lock

Only works when used by the original creator.

6. Timing Collapse

Good construct deployed at the wrong rhythm or wrong moment.

7. Propagation Drift

Others can use it, but its invariants dissolve in the process.

